05/02/2007
BELGRADE, Serbia -- The Military Archives provided the UN war crimes tribunal with access to 8,445 documents -- a total of 44,000 pages -- in 2006, according to Colonel Dragan Krsmanovic, head of the Serbian institution. 
In a statement Friday (February 2nd), he said access was part of Belgrade's obligation to fully co-operate with the tribunal. 
In addition, he said, the military archives granted the Military Intelligence Agency and domestic courts access to more than 1,000 documents.
In other news, the OSCE Mission to Serbia and the Serbian War Crimes Prosecutor's Office organised a meeting in Belgrade on Monday of war crimes prosecutors from Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia and Serbia. 
The event was aimed at boosting regional co-operation. 
(B92 - 04/02/07; Tanjug, OSCE website - 02/02/07)
